body:
Currently both the API and web client have a lot of logic dealing with board geometry. 
___
The API has a very minimal model, roughly:

```
type Location { x : int; y : int; region : int }

type Cell { id : int, locations : List<Location> }

type Board { cells : List<Cell>; regionCount: int }
```

This minimal model describes the grid coordinates of cells used by the game engine, which uses discrete integer values for everything. This is enough to calculate available moves, event effects, etc.
__
The web client needs to extend this model to be able to draw the board:
```
type CellType { Even | Odd | Center }

type Point { x : float; y : float }

type Polygon { vertices : List<Point> }

type CellView {
    id : int
    locations : List<Location>
    polygon : Polygon
    type : CellType
    isSelected : bool
    isSelectable : bool
    piece : Option<Piece>
}

type BoardView { regionCount : int; cells : List<CellView> }
```
___

Consider moving more of the client's model and related logic into the API. 

Reasons:
- If a 2nd client ever gets created, like in Kotlin or Swift, it would be nice to not have 2 copies of this logic to maintain.
- F# seems like it would be a good choice for this kind of math-based work. Safer and easier to debug than TypeScript.
- The whole geometric construction of the board is essentially static data. At runtime a client may want to resize or rotate the board, move pieces, or show highlights in selectable cells. But the proportions of the board, which is the hard part never changes. This could be cached indefinitely in the API.

The new API model might be like
```
type GridLocation { x : int; y : int; region : int }

type Point { x : float; y : float }

type Polygon { vertices : List<Point> }

type Cell { 
    id : int
    locations : List<GridLocation> 
    polygon : Polygon
    type : CellType
}

type Board { cells : List<Cell>; regionCount: int }
```

The web could combine the with the `Game` to find the other properties in a `CellView` (`piece`, `isSelected`, `isSelectable`) which may change over the course of a game.
